\begin_layout Standard
Example 1.
 (Hypothesis Testing) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

: some model 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\theta)$
\end_inset

 with a set of parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\{\theta_{1},\cdots,\theta_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 of precision 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
number 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 may vary and influence the description complexity of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if we want to determine the distribution of the length of beans,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a normal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 with parameter median 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

and variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 So essentially we have to determine the correct hypothesis described by
 identifying the type of distribution(normal) and the correct parameter
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In such cased, we minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $-logP(D|\theta)-logP(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example 2.(Fitting of a 'best' polynomial on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 given sample points in the 2-dimensional plane.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,\cdots,n-1$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the best polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, fitting on points 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{i},y_{i})(1\leq i\leq n)$
\end_inset

, which minimizes the error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $error(f_{k})=\Sigma_{i=1}^{n}(f_{k}(x_{i})-y_{i})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume each coefficient takes 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 bits, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 is encoded in 
\begin_inset Formula $c(k+1)$
\end_inset

 bits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(y_{1},\cdots,y_{n}|f,x_{1},\cdots,x_{n})=\prod exp\{-O[(f(x_{i})-y_{i})^{2}]\}$
\end_inset

.(measurement with Gaussian/normal errors), so 
\begin_inset Formula $-log(Pr(y_{1},\cdots,y_{n}|f,x_{1},\cdots,x_{n}))=c'error(f)$
\end_inset

 for some computable 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MDL principle tells us to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f_{m}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\{0,\cdots,n-1\}$
\end_inset

, which minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $c(m+1)+c'error(f_{m})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example 3.(Derivation of code length expression for choosing knots in regression
 spline smoothing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L(y)=L$
\end_inset

(fitted model)
\begin_inset Formula $+L$
\end_inset

(data given the fitted model)
\begin_inset Formula $=L(\hat{\theta})+L(y|\hat{\theta})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{\theta})=L(\hat{r})+L(\hat{m})+L(\hat{k}|\hat{m})+L(\hat{b},\hat{\beta}|\hat{r},\hat{m},\hat{k})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
code length for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{r})+L(\hat{m})$
\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
use 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\{0,1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Longrightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{r})=-log_{2}\frac{1}{4}=log_{2}4=2$
\end_inset

 bits, a constant that will be ignored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}$
\end_inset

 is an integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{m})=L^{*}(\hat{m})=log_{2}c+log_{2}\hat{m}+log_{2}log_{2}\hat{m}+\cdots$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\approx2.865$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{*}(\hat{m})\approx log_{2}\hat{m}$
\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}$
\end_inset

 is reasonably large.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{r})+L(\hat{m})\approx log_{2}\hat{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
code length for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{k}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{k}|\hat{m})$
\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{k_{1}},\dots,\hat{k_{\hat{m}}}\}$
\end_inset

 is restricted to be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{1},\cdots,x_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{k}|\hat{m})=L(\hat{l_{1}},\cdots,\hat{l_{\hat{m}}}|\hat{m})=\Sigma_{j=1}^{\hat{m}}L^{*}(\hat{l_{j}})\approx\Sigma_{j=1}^{\hat{m}}log_{2}\hat{l_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{l_{j}}$
\end_inset

(integers) is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th successive 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

index difference
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

's which satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{k_{j-1}}\leq x_{i}<\hat{k_{j}},j=1,\cdots,\hat{m};\hat{k_{0}}=min(x_{i}),\hat{k_{\hat{m}+1}}=max(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(complete knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{l_{1}},\cdots,\hat{l_{\hat{m}}}$
\end_inset

implies complete knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{k}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
code length for 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{b},\hat{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{r},\hat{m},\hat{k}\}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $L(\hat{b},\hat{\beta}|\hat{r},\hat{m},\hat{k})$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
each of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{b},\hat{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

- 
